me: Argh! Why is this script not working? What's different? Why is there no data?

me 10 minutes later: Oh. Set the working directory.

The reason for ~/Rlibs failing "eventually" is that when a new big release of #RStats is released (in April each year), many packages installed in the old version (e.g. R 3.6.3) are incompatible with R 4.0.*. (We all need to reinstall all our packages once a year to avoid this)

TIP: Unless you really^6 know what ur doing, don't using .libPaths() or set R_LIBS_USER etc to change were #RStats installs pkgs. I see sooo many people installing to ~/Rlibs & other non-version specific folders eventually resulting in "randomly" broken pkgs

Use R's defaults =😀

@klmr I think .libPaths() makes it confusing. On a fresh account, we get

> .libPaths()
"/usr/lib/R/library"

but if we run install.packages(), #RStats will ask us:

Would you like to use a personal library instead? (yes/No/cancel)

answering 'yes' => default folder under ~/R created

But yeah, you found the right one.

@dr_becker @rstats4ds @FC_rstats Like I said in the beginning: Tidy users seem to love to abstract away their data, as if it's the only thing that exists in the universe.  They have this pile of data, and they want to subset it and do something with it and never think of it again...

@dr_becker @rstats4ds @FC_rstats ...the simple reality is, many people in "modern" data science (and perhaps practically all tidyverse users?) abstract away their data.  It's just some thing to be acted upon, instead of modeled.  But that's a shame, because often times modeling data as a "thing" is useful!
@FC_rstats I — or basically anyone who studied CS pre pandas or tidyverse — went the other direction.

@dr_becker @rstats4ds @FC_rstats (It just takes more work to provide the interface)

You can't say:

select OUTCOME from plays where ID = "1234"
 
isn't any better or worse than

plays(id=1234).get_outcome()

or 

[however %> the %> heck %> you'd do this in %> R].

They all have their uses...perhaps even R 😝

@dr_becker @rstats4ds @FC_rstats Sure, and that's a common thought pattern amongst Tidyverse/R users.  What you're saying is 100% and makes sense, but it's unfortunately somewhat one-dimensional.  There are plenty of other considerations: Code clarity, providing a coherent API for other systems, robustness, etc.

@dr_becker @rstats4ds @FC_rstats Just that many (most?) computer science curriculum up until very recently considered object oriented programming design foundational. The alternatives — functional programming, etc. — didn’t have much to with data management. It was basically just OOP + databases.

@dr_becker @rstats4ds @FC_rstats ...that's a perfectly reasonable point of view, and in that context Tidy (or pandas, etc.) works beautifully!

But it is actually a tiny -- trust me on this one -- fraction of what gets done with software development, and in most other cases, a different paradigm is preferable.

@mr_le_fox @dr_becker @rstats4ds @FC_rstats 100% agree.  I've been harping on the NFL analytics community for years over how they take inherently hierarchical data and flatten it because...they can't really think in any other paradigm other than CSVs.  It doesn't make a ton of sense to me, but I've clearly lost that fight!
